Lets look at the distribution of each variables, starting with the categorical variables.

  • BMI category
df %>% ggplot(aes(bmi_category,fill=bmi_category)) + geom_bar()

We have two categories for normal weight. We will combine those into one.

df$bmi_category = ifelse(df$bmi_category=="Normal"|df$bmi_category=="Normal Weight", "Normal", df$bmi_category)
df %>% ggplot(aes(bmi_category,fill=bmi_category)) + geom_bar()

  • Blood Pressure
df %>% ggplot(aes(blood_pressure, fill=blood_pressure)) + geom_bar() + coord_flip()

Majority of individuals in our dataset have a higher than normal blood pressure, above 120/80. We also have to transform this variable into three new categories: Normal, Elevated, and Hypertension. This will also improve the performance of our classification model.

df = df %>% separate_wider_delim(blood_pressure, delim ='/',names = c("systolic", "diastolic"))

df <- df %>% mutate(
  blood_pressure = case_when(
    as.numeric(systolic) < 120 & as.numeric(diastolic) < 80 ~ "Normal",
    as.numeric(systolic) >= 130 & as.numeric(diastolic) >= 89 ~ "Hypertension",
    TRUE ~ "Elevated"
  )
)

df %>% ggplot(aes(blood_pressure, fill=blood_pressure)) + geom_bar() + coord_flip()

This is consistent with our initial observation that the majority of dataset has higher than normal blood pressure.

  • Sleep disorder (our target variable)
df %>% ggplot(aes(sleep_disorder, fill=sleep_disorder)) + geom_bar()

Due to the size of our dataset, we will create a new target variable based on the sleep disorder variable. This will allow us to build a more robust model.

# renaming "sleep_disorder" to "disorder_type"
df = df %>% 
  rename(disorder_type = sleep_disorder) %>% 
  mutate(sleep_disorder = ifelse(disorder_type=="Sleep Apnea"|disorder_type=="Insomnia","yes","no"))

Considering the context of our analysis, we will prioritize measurement variables over the variables that represent subjective ratings.

Due to our sample size, will use cross validation to train our model. But first, to simplify the feature selection process, we will use the random forest variable importance method to select the most important variables for our model.

library(randomForest)
randomForest 4.7-1.1
Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.

Attaching package: randomForest

The following object is masked from package:dplyr:

    combine

The following object is masked from package:ggplot2:

    margin
rf_model = randomForest(sleep_disorder~., data=train_df, importance=TRUE, ntree=100)
rf_varImp = importance(rf_model)
rf_varImp <- data.frame(Feature=rownames(rf_varImp), Importance=rf_varImp[,1])
rf_varImp$Importance <- round(rf_varImp$Importance / max(rf_varImp$Importance) * 100, 2)
rf_varImp <- rf_varImp[order(rf_varImp$Importance, decreasing = TRUE), ]
rf_varImp

Summary of our models

# Create an empty dataframe to store the results
results_df <- data.frame(Model = character(),
                         Accuracy = numeric(),
                         Kappa = numeric(),
                         AIC = numeric(),
                         stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Loop through each model
n=3
for (i in 1:n) {
  # Get the model object
  model <- get(paste0("model", i))
  
  # Extract the accuracy, kappa, and AIC values
  accuracy <- model[["results"]][["Accuracy"]]
  kappa <- model[["results"]][["Kappa"]]
  aic <- model[["finalModel"]][["aic"]]
  
  # Create a row of data with the model name and the corresponding values
  row <- data.frame(Model = paste0("model", i),
                    Accuracy = accuracy,
                    Kappa = kappa,
                    AIC = aic)
  
  # Append the row to the results dataframe
  results_df <- rbind(results_df, row)
}

results_df

Model 2 has higher accuracy and kappa score. However, this model is affected by the presence of too many predictor variables which is evident in the higher AIC score.

All three models would work great. However, we will go with the second model because of its overall good performance.

  • BMI

According to our data, the log odds of having a sleep disorder for a person who is overweight is 1.41 times the odds of a person of normal weight. The odds ratio of a person who is overweight are 4.11 times those of a person of normal weight. So, a person who is overweight is 3.11% more likely to have a sleep disorder relative to a person of normal weight.

Moreover, the log odds of having a sleep disorder for a person who is obese is 31.91 times the odds of a person of normal weight. The odds ratio of a person who is obese is 718.33 times those of a person of normal weight. Therefore, individuals who are obese have a significantly higher likelihood of experiencing a sleep disorder, with a staggering percentage change of -718327.92% compared to individuals of normal weight.

  • Occupation

Doctors had the highest number of individuals without any sleep disorders among all categories. Thus, were used as our reference category.

Our findings indicate that, compared to doctors, engineers have a log odds of having a sleep disorder that is 1.9 times the odds of individuals in other occupations. The odds ratio for engineers is 6.71, implying that they have 6.71 times the odds of developing a sleep disorder compared to doctors. This represents a percentage change of -5.71%, meaning that engineers are 5.71% more likely to have a sleep disorder than individuals in other professions.

The log odds of having a sleep disorder for managers have a log odds of having a sleep disorder that is -16.27 times the odds for doctors. The odds ratio for managers is 0, indicating that they have zero odds of developing a sleep disorder compared to doctors. This corresponds to a percentage change of 1.00%, suggesting that managers are 1% less likely to have a sleep disorder relative to doctors.

In summary, certain occupations such as Engineers, lawyers, accountants, nurses, teachers, scientists, and salespeople have a higher likelihood, in varying percentages, of having a sleep disorder relative to doctors having the same sleep disorder. Whereas occupations such as Software Engineers, Managers, and Sales Representatives have a lower likelihood of having a sleep disorder relative to doctors.

  • Sleep Duration

Based on our data, for each unit increase in sleep duration, the log odds of having a sleep disorder decrease by a factor of -0.75. The odds ratio for sleep duration is 0.47, indicating that with each unit increase in sleep duration, the odds of having a sleep disorder decrease by a factor of 0.47. This corresponds to a percentage change of 0.53%, suggesting that longer sleep duration is associated with a 0.53% reduction in the likelihood of experiencing a sleep disorder.

  • Blood PressureElevated

Our findings indicate that the log odds of having a sleep disorder for individuals with elevated blood pressure are 2.31 times the log odds of individuals with normal blood pressure. The odds ratio for elevated blood pressure is 10.03, suggesting that individuals with elevated blood pressure have 10.03 times the odds of developing a sleep disorder compared to individuals with normal blood pressure. This corresponds to a percentage change of -9.03%, indicating that elevated blood pressure increases the likelihood of having a sleep disorder by 9.03%.

  • Blood PressureHypertension

According to our data, individuals with hypertension have a log odds of having a sleep disorder that is 3.75 times the log odds of individuals with normal blood pressure. The odds ratio for hypertension is 4.24, indicating that individuals with hypertension have 4.24 times the odds of developing a sleep disorder compared to individuals with normal blood pressure. This corresponds to a substantial percentage change of -41.40%, suggesting that an individual with hypertension is 41.40% more likely to have a sleep disorder.

  • Physical Activity Level

Based on our findings, for each unit increase in physical activity level, which is the number of minutes spent on physical activities daily, the log odds of having a sleep disorder decrease by a factor of 0.01. The odds ratio for physical activity level is 0.99, indicating that with each unit increase in physical activity level, the odds of having a sleep disorder decrease by a factor of 0.99. This corresponds to a percentage change of 0.01%, suggesting that higher physical activity levels reduced the likelihood of experiencing a sleep disorder by 0.01%.

In conclusion, these variables prove to be effective in identifying individuals with sleep disorders. With additional data, it may be possible to utilize these variables in an attempt to identify specific types of sleep disorders that individuals may have.
